{{About|the speed skating oval in Albertville, France|the speed skating oval in Grenoble, France|L'Anneau de Vitesse}} {{Infobox stadium | name = L'anneau de vitesse | nickname = | image = Stade de Patinage Olympique (2007).jpg | image_size = 250px | fullname = Anneau de Vitesse du Sauvay | former_names = | location = |coordinates = {{coord|45|39|50.52|N|6|22|15.23|E|region:FR-73_type:landmark_scale:2000|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1991 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | construction_cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | landscape architect = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | tenants = }}
'''L'anneau de vitesse''' ({{Language with name/for||French|speed oval}}) was a [[speed skating]] venue located in [[Albertville]], [[France]]. As of the [[2018 Winter Olympics]], it is the last outdoor venue to hold [[Speed skating at the Winter Olympics|speed skating]] as all following Olympic events have been held indoors. For the [[1992 Winter Olympics]], they hosted the [[Speed skating at the 1992 Winter Olympics|speed skating]] events.
The stands, which remain present, were constructed as an [[airfoil]] from [[aerospace]] designs. The ice was made using {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} of piping using R32 and [[brine]] [[refrigeration]] to cool the track to between {{Convert|−5|and|−8|C|F|abbr=on}} with {{convert|4|cm|in|abbr=on|adj=mid|-thick}} ice. Before this the surface was covered with {{convert|1.20|m|ftin|abbr=on}} of base sand in order to lay down the piping.
The track is now a multipurpose stadium used for [[athletics (sport)|athletics]] and [[association football|football]] events.
