{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox sportsperson |name=Michel Vaarten |image=Michel Vaarten 2015 (cropped).jpg |caption=Vaarten in 2015 |birth_date={{birth date and age|1957|1|17|df=yes}} |birth_place=[[Turnhout]], [[Belgium]] |death_date= |death_place= |show-medals=yes |medaltemplates= {{MedalSport | Men's [[track cycling]]}} {{MedalCountry | {{BEL}} }} {{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}} {{MedalSilver| [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Cycling at the 1976 Summer Olympics – Men's 1000m time trial|1.000m Time Trial]]}} }}
'''Michel Vaarten''' (born 17 January 1957) is a retired [[track cyclist]] and [[road bicycle racer]] from [[Belgium]]. He represented Belgium at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal, Quebec]], Canada, where he won silver medal in the [[Cycling at the 1976 Summer Olympics – Men's 1000m time trial|1.000m time trial]] behind East Germany's [[Klaus-Jürgen Grünke]].<ref name="SportsRef">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/va/michel-vaarten-1.html |title=Michel Vaarten Olympic Results |accessdate=26 April 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref> Vaarten was a professional from 1979 to 1992. He won 12 national titles, one European title and one world title, mainly in track cycling. Vaarten is currently piloting a Derny bike in many Six Day Cycling events around Europe.
After his competitive career, he served as a pacemaker.<ref>[https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20141118_01383027 Dernykoning Michel Vaarten schuwt risico’s]. Nieuwsblad (2014-11-19). Retrieved 2018-05-24.</ref>
