{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Rose Brothers Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]], [[Lincolnshire]] | coord = {{coord|53.4100|-0.7892|display=inline}} | establishment = 1851 (first recorded match) | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year2 = 1931 & 1937 | club2 = [[Minor Counties]] | year1 = 1927-1954 & 1960-1961 | club1 = [[Lincolnshire County Cricket Club|Lincolnshire]] | date = 18 August | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/486.html Ground profile }}
'''Rose Brothers Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]], [[Lincolnshire]]. The first recorded match on the ground was in 1851, when Gainsborough played an [[All-England Eleven]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/486_misc.html Other matches played on Rose Brothers Ground]</ref> The first [[Minor Counties Championship]] match played at the ground saw [[Lincolnshire County Cricket Club|Lincolnshire]] play [[Bedfordshire County Cricket Club|Bedfordshire]] in 1927. From 1927 to 1961, the ground hosted 18 Minor Counties Championship matches, the last of which saw Lincolnshire play [[Shropshire County Cricket Club|Shropshire]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/486_minc.html Minor Counties Championship Matches played on Rose Brothers Ground]</ref>
The ground also held two [[first-class cricket|first-class]] matches, the first of which came in 1931 between a combined [[Minor Counties cricket team|Minor Counties]] team and the touring [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealanders]]. The second first-class fixture held at the ground came in 1937 and was between the same sides as the 1931 fixture.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/486_f.html First-Class Matches played on Rose Brothers Ground]</ref> The ground closed after the Rose Foxgrove company concentrated its production<ref>http://www.bpsh.net</ref> at Leeds in 1987
